@page "/help/accounting"
@attribute [Authorize]

<PageTitle>Accounting Workflows</PageTitle>

<section class="page-shell">
    <header class="page-header">
        <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Accounting Workflows</p>
            <h1>Run the modules as one accounting system, not isolated islands.</h1>
        </div>
        <p class="page-intro">
            Good workflow means entering activity in the right place, reviewing the right reports, and resolving
            exceptions before they drift into payroll, tax filing, or month-end close.
        </p>
    </header>

    <section class="content-grid">
        <article class="panel">
            <h2>Ledger and receivables</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Use ledger entries for true journal activity, accruals, and controlled adjustments.</li>
                <li>Review trial balance and journal detail after significant postings.</li>
                <li>Create invoices with complete customer detail and apply cash promptly.</li>
                <li>Separate disputes, write-offs, and unapplied cash instead of blending them together.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
            <h2>Payables and operations</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Enter bills with due dates, references, and approval state intact.</li>
                <li>Keep vendor credits visible until they are intentionally applied.</li>
                <li>Use operations pages to track inventory, open orders, and fulfillment blockers.</li>
                <li>Resolve stock exceptions before promising ship dates or printing shipment documents.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="content-grid">
        <article class="panel">
            <h2>Payroll and taxes</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Verify employee setup, withholding assignments, and deductions before each payroll run.</li>
                <li>Review gross-to-net, liabilities, and exception output before finalizing paychecks.</li>
                <li>Keep generally published tax content separate from employer-specific rates and notices.</li>
                <li>Treat tax updates as accounting changes with reporting consequences, not cosmetic data refreshes.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="panel">
            <h2>Projects and close</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Group labor, materials, billing, and profitability by project or job.</li>
                <li>Keep time, cost, and invoice timing aligned so margin reports remain credible.</li>
                <li>Reconcile receivables and payables to control accounts at month-end.</li>
                <li>Review financial statements only after subledger and payroll obligations are in line.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>
</section>
